nl.uu.cs.ape.sat.models.logic.constructs

Class Literal

  • java.lang.Object
    • nl.uu.cs.ape.sat.models.logic.constructs.Literal
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Comparable<Literal>

    public class Literal
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable<Literal>
    The Literal class represents literals (atoms that can be negated) corresponding to the usage of the modules and types in the solution. It is of the form Predicate(Attribute) where Predicate represents a single predicate/label used to depict AbstractModule, Module or Type, while State represents the state in the module/type automaton where the module/type is used (or not used if the literal is negative). The second attribute (referedStateArgument) is optional and used when the Literal represent the type that is used as tool input - referred state is the state when the type was created.

    Literals can start with a negation.

    Literals are compared according to the state in which they are used (#usedInStateArgument), i.e. a literal that represents the n-th state in the workflow, comes before the literal that represents the (n+1)th state.
    Author:
    Vedran Kasalica

      • compareTo

        public int compareTo(Literal otherLiteral)
        Compare the two Literals according to the state they are used in. Returns a negative integer, zero, or a positive integer as this Literal's state comes before than, is equal to, or comes after than the @otherLiteral's state.
        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable<Literal>
        Parameters:
        otherLiteral - - the Literal to be compared
        Returns:
        The value 0 if the argument Literal's state is equal to this Literal's state; a value less than 0 if this Literal's state comes before the @otherLiteral's state; and a value greater than 0 if this Literal's state comes after the @otherLiteral's state.
